## Download data {#sec-download_data_ve}

First, you need to download some animal location data from the [Movebank database]( https://www.movebank.org/). This is a public database of animal location tracking data from different studies, in a standardised format to encourage data reuse.

To find your dataset:

* On the MoveBank Site, click on "Data" and then "View and Manage Studies". 
* Select "Studies where I can download any data"
* Choose a study from the list. Search for an animal which interests you. Choose a study containing approximately 5–15 tracked individuals (shown in the "Number of Animals" field on the website). This will give enough data to produce an interesting plot without making it difficult to interpret.

In this exercise, based on this data frame, you will plot the median location of each individual animal by date as a scatter plot overlaid onto a map.

First, download the CSV file and rename it so there are no gaps in the file name, then put it into the data directory for Practical 2.

## Read Data {#sec-read_data_ve}

Read the data frame into a variable.

This data has a couple of features you've not come across yet, so we'll provide some code to help you:

* The column names are not in a format that R can easily use, as they contain hyphens (`-`). We can use an additional function, `clean_names()` to rename the columns. `clean_names()` converts column names into a consistent format by replacing spaces and punctuation with underscores and converting everything to lower case.

* One of the columns contains date information which needs to be reformated - we do this using the `mutate()` function and the `as_date()` function. We'll learn more about the `mutate()` function in a later practical.

In the below, replace `seals.csv` with the filename of the data frame you have downloaded.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
locations <- read_csv("data/seals.csv") |>
  clean_names() |>
  mutate(Date = as_date(timestamp))
```

